 {"id":"bd-1lk","title":"Create theme system with SdTheme struct","description":"# Create theme system with SdTheme struct

## Purpose
Define a cohesive visual identity for the Stream Deck CLI through a centralized theme system. This ensures consistent colors, styles, and visual elements across all commands.

## Background

### Why a Theme System?
Without centralized theme management:
- Colors would be scattered across multiple files
- Changing the visual identity would require editing many places
- Inconsistent styling would create a disjointed experience

### Design Philosophy
The theme should feel:
- **Premium**: High-quality, polished appearance
- **Technical**: Appropriate for a developer tool
- **Branded**: Subtle Stream Deck identity (blue accent)
- **Accessible**: Works on various terminal color schemes

## Technical Details

### Module Structure
```
src/theme/
├── mod.rs       # SdTheme struct and Default impl
└── (future: additional themes if needed)
```

### SdTheme Struct (src/theme/mod.rs)
```rust
use rich_rust::prelude::*;

/// Visual theme for Stream Deck CLI human-mode output
/// 
/// This struct centralizes all colors and styles used throughout
/// the CLI, ensuring visual consistency and easy customization.
pub struct SdTheme {
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // Brand Colors
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    /// Primary accent color (Stream Deck blue)
    /// Used for: headers, panel borders, highlights
    pub accent: Color,

    /// Success color (green)
    /// Used for: success messages, checkmarks, positive states
    pub success: Color,

    /// Error color (red)
    /// Used for: error messages, X marks, negative states
    pub error: Color,

    /// Warning color (amber)
    /// Used for: warnings, key indices, attention items
    pub warning: Color,

    /// Muted color (gray)
    /// Used for: timestamps, secondary info, hints
    pub muted: Color,

    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // Component Styles
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    /// Style for section headers
    /// Applied to: device names, section titles
    pub header: Style,

    /// Style for labels/keys in key-value pairs
    /// Applied to: "Serial:", "Firmware:", etc.
    pub label: Style,

    /// Style for values in key-value pairs
    /// Applied to: actual serial numbers, versions, etc.
    pub value: Style,

    /// Style for key indices (0-31)
    /// Applied to: key numbers in events and operations
    pub key_index: Style,

    /// Style for device serial numbers
    /// Applied to: serial number display
    pub device_serial: Style,

    /// Style for brightness values
    /// Applied to: brightness percentage
    pub brightness: Style,

    /// Style for button press events
    /// Applied to: "pressed" state indicator
    pub button_pressed: Style,

    /// Style for button release events
    /// Applied to: "released" state indicator
    pub button_released: Style,

    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // Box Drawing
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════

    /// Box character set for panels and tables
    /// Default: ROUNDED (╭─╮) for modern terminals
    /// Fallback: ASCII (+--+) when safe_box is enabled
    pub box_style: &'static BoxChars,
}
```

### Color Palette
```rust
impl Default for SdTheme {
    fn default() -> Self {
        // Helper to parse color or panic (these are constants, so safe)
        let color = |hex: &str| Color::parse(hex).expect("invalid theme color");

        Self {
            // Brand colors - carefully chosen for terminal visibility
            accent: color("#0080FF"),     // Stream Deck blue
            success: color("#00D26A"),    // Vibrant green
            error: color("#FF4757"),      // Soft red (not harsh)
            warning: color("#FFA502"),    // Amber/orange
            muted: color("#747D8C"),      // Medium gray

            // Component styles built from brand colors
            header: Style::new()
                .bold()
                .color(color("#0080FF")),

            label: Style::new()
                .dim(),

            value: Style::new()
                .bold(),

            key_index: Style::new()
                .bold()
                .color(color("#FFA502")),

            device_serial: Style::new()
                .italic()
                .color(color("#747D8C")),

            brightness: Style::new()
                .bold()
                .color(color("#00D26A")),

            button_pressed: Style::new()
                .bold()
                .color(color("#00D26A")),

            button_released: Style::new()
                .dim(),

            box_style: &BoxChars::ROUNDED,
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage Pattern
```rust
let theme = SdTheme::default();

// Use in output formatting
let mut text = Text::new("");
text.append_styled("Serial: ", theme.label.clone());
text.append_styled(&device.serial, theme.device_serial.clone());

// Use colors for panels
let panel = Panel::from_text("content")
    .border_style(Style::new().color(theme.accent));
```

## Color Selection Rationale

### Accent (#0080FF)
- Stream Deck devices feature blue LED backlighting
- Blue conveys technology, reliability, precision
- High visibility on both light and dark backgrounds

### Success (#00D26A)
- Standard "green = good" convention
- Bright enough to stand out
- Not so bright as to be harsh

### Error (#FF4757)
- Soft red that draws attention without being alarming
- Readable against dark backgrounds
- Not pure red (#FF0000) which can be harsh

### Warning (#FFA502)
- Amber/orange for caution
- Distinct from both error (red) and success (green)
- Used for key indices to make them pop

### Muted (#747D8C)
- Medium gray for secondary information
- Readable but doesn't compete with primary content
- Works on both light and dark terminals

## Implementation Steps
1. Create src/theme/ directory
2. Create src/theme/mod.rs with SdTheme struct
3. Implement Default trait with color palette
4. Add mod theme; to main module
5. Test color rendering in terminal

